  <h1>Riyadh Expat Guide 2026: Salaries, Cost of Living, and Lifestyle</h1>

  <p>Riyadh is the epicenter of Saudi Arabia's Vision 2030 transformation and one of the fastest-growing cities in the world. The capital hosts over 7 million residents and is rapidly evolving from a government-focused city into a global business, entertainment, and technology hub. With tax-free salaries, dramatically lower living costs than Dubai, and career opportunities tied to trillion-dollar mega-projects, Riyadh is increasingly the first choice for ambitious expat professionals seeking impact and financial reward. The city's skyline changes visibly month by month as new towers, entertainment districts, and infrastructure projects take shape across the capital.</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-8"><CostOfLivingSimulator client:idle defaultCity="riyadh" /></div>

  <h2>Riyadh Salary Overview</h2>
  <p>Riyadh salaries average SAR 12,500 (~€3,000) per month, with Vision 2030-linked roles paying significant premiums. PIF (Public Investment Fund) portfolio companies, NEOM project offices in Riyadh, and the growing tech ecosystem offer competitive packages. Software engineers earn SAR 14,000-22,000 (~€3,360-5,280), with senior roles at companies like STC, Elm, and Tamara reaching SAR 30,000+ (~€7,200+). Healthcare professionals are well-compensated, with doctors at Ministry of Health hospitals earning SAR 18,000-40,000 (~€4,320-9,600). Financial services roles in the expanding capital markets sector pay SAR 15,000-30,000 (~€3,600-7,200). Many employers provide compound housing or housing allowances that effectively add 30-40% to the total package value. The zero income tax environment means gross salary equals take-home pay, with no GOSI deductions for expatriates.</p>
  <p>Additional salary benchmarks for Riyadh in 2026: senior project managers on giga-projects earn SAR 25,000-45,000 (~€6,000-10,800), cybersecurity specialists at SAR 18,000-32,000 (~€4,320-7,680), marketing managers at SAR 14,000-22,000 (~€3,360-5,280), international school teachers at SAR 9,000-15,000 (~€2,160-3,600), and HR managers at SAR 12,000-20,000 (~€2,880-4,800). The entertainment sector, virtually nonexistent before 2017, now offers roles in event management, content creation, and hospitality at SAR 10,000-25,000 (~€2,400-6,000). Many Riyadh employers, particularly government-linked entities, offer 13th-month salaries, Ramadan bonuses, and performance-linked annual increments that can add 10-20% to total annual compensation.</p>

  <CostOfLivingBreakdown city="Riyadh" country="saudi-arabia" />

  <h2>Cost of Living in Riyadh</h2>
  <p>Riyadh offers the best cost-to-salary ratio among major Gulf cities. A one-bedroom apartment in popular areas like Olaya, Al Malqa, or Al Nakheel costs SAR 2,500-5,000 (~€600-1,200) per month, roughly 40-60% less than equivalent Dubai neighborhoods. Compound villas in the Diplomatic Quarter or Riyadh compounds run SAR 10,000-20,000 (~€2,400-4,800). See our <a href="/saudi-arabia/housing/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Saudi housing guide</a> for a full breakdown of compound vs. apartment living. Groceries cost SAR 800-1,800 (~€192-432) per month at Panda, Tamimi Markets, or LuLu. Dining is affordable, with budget meals at SAR 15-30 (~€4-7) and mid-range restaurants at SAR 60-150 (~€14-36). The 15% VAT applies to most goods and services, which is higher than the UAE's 5%. <a href="/saudi-arabia/utilities/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Utilities</a> through SEC average SAR 300-800 (~€72-192) monthly. A single professional can live comfortably on SAR 5,500-8,000 (~€1,320-1,920) per month, while families should budget SAR 12,000-22,000 (~€2,880-5,280).</p>
  <p>A practical monthly budget for a single professional living in Al Malqa: rent SAR 3,500 (~€840), utilities SAR 350 (~€84), groceries SAR 1,000 (~€240), dining out SAR 800 (~€192), transport including fuel SAR 500 (~€120), mobile phone SAR 150 (~€36), gym membership SAR 200 (~€48), and miscellaneous SAR 400 (~€96), totalling approximately SAR 6,900 (~€1,656). This leaves substantial room for savings on a salary of SAR 12,000+ (~€2,880+). For families, add school fees of SAR 2,000-5,000 (~€480-1,200) per month when averaged annually, plus additional groceries and household expenses. Coffee culture has exploded in Riyadh, with specialty cafes on every corner charging SAR 18-30 (~€4-7) for a flat white, while cinema tickets at VOX or AMC run SAR 55-75 (~€13-18).</p>

  <h2>Neighborhoods and Housing</h2>
  <p>Riyadh's compound communities are the traditional expat housing choice, offering self-contained environments with pools, gyms, restaurants, and social facilities within secure gated perimeters. The Diplomatic Quarter (DQ) is the most prestigious compound area, housing embassies and senior diplomatic and corporate staff, with villas at SAR 15,000-25,000 (~€3,600-6,000) per month. Arizona Compound, Al Hamra Compound, and Eid Compound are well-known Western expat communities with extensive amenities. Al Malqa and Hittin are newer, upscale residential areas north of the city with modern apartments and villas, increasingly popular with professionals who prefer non-compound living. Olaya and Al Tahlia Street form the commercial and social heart of Riyadh with apartment living, close to restaurants, malls, and the financial district. KAFD (King Abdullah Financial District) is emerging as a premium mixed-use development with luxury apartments, office towers, and retail, positioned as Riyadh's answer to Dubai's DIFC. Al Yasmin and Al Narjis offer family-friendly villas at moderate prices of SAR 6,000-12,000 (~€1,440-2,880). For budget-conscious expats, Al Aqiq and Al Wadi provide good value with one-bedroom apartments from SAR 2,000 (~€480).</p>
  <p>Choosing between compound and non-compound living is a fundamental decision for Riyadh expats. Compounds offer a familiar, community-oriented environment with immediate social connections, children's play areas, and freedoms within the compound walls (including mixed-gender swimming and more relaxed dress codes). Non-compound living offers more independence, better access to city amenities, and often newer, more modern accommodation. Families with young children often prefer compounds for the built-in community and safety, while single professionals and couples may enjoy the flexibility of apartment living in neighborhoods like Al Malqa or Olaya. Rent is typically paid in two to four annual installments, and a security deposit equivalent to one month's rent is standard.</p>

  <h2>Commuting and Transportation</h2>
  <p>Riyadh is a car-dependent city, though the situation is changing with the Riyadh Metro expansion. The metro system, with six lines covering 176 km, is progressively opening and will greatly improve transportation when fully operational. Until then, most expats drive or use ride-hailing through Uber and Careem. See our <a href="/guides/driving-licence/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">driving licence guide</a> for the Saudi conversion process. Traffic peaks are 7:00-9:00 AM and 4:00-6:00 PM on the King Fahd Road and Northern Ring Road. A typical commute from Al Malqa to KAFD takes 15-25 minutes, while the DQ to Olaya run is 20-30 minutes. Fuel is extremely cheap at SAR 2.18 (~€0.52) per liter for 91 octane, making car ownership affordable. Car insurance ranges from SAR 1,000-3,000 (~€240-720) annually for comprehensive coverage. There are no road tolls in Riyadh, unlike Dubai's Salik system. Parking is free in most areas, including many malls and office buildings. The Saptco bus network operates limited routes, and the planned Riyadh Bus Rapid Transit system will complement the metro when completed.</p>

  <h2>Working in Riyadh</h2>
  <p>Riyadh's job market is driven by government and government-linked entities. Saudi Aramco, PIF, NEOM, and various ministries are major employers. The tech ecosystem is growing rapidly with support from the Communications, Space, and Technology Commission, and Riyadh is positioning itself as a regional tech hub, with companies like Careem, Noon, and international tech firms establishing or expanding operations. Financial services are expanding through the Saudi Exchange (Tadawul) and growing capital markets, with Riyadh aiming to become a regional financial center. Saudization (Nitaqat) requires companies to meet minimum quotas of Saudi employees, but specialist international roles remain widely available in technology, healthcare, engineering, and management. The work week is Sunday to Thursday, though some international companies have shifted to Monday to Friday. Working hours during Ramadan are reduced by two hours per day.</p>
  <p>The Regional Headquarters (RHQ) program, requiring multinational companies to establish their Middle East headquarters in Riyadh by 2024, has brought dozens of major international firms to the capital, creating new demand for senior management, finance, legal, and operations professionals. Companies including Bechtel, PwC, Deloitte, Boston Consulting Group, and many others have expanded their Riyadh offices, adding thousands of international professional roles to the market.</p>

  <h2>Schools and Education</h2>
  <p>Riyadh has a growing network of international schools. The British International School of Riyadh (BISR) and the American International School Riyadh (AISR) are among the most established, with fees of SAR 30,000-65,000 (~€7,200-15,600) per year. King Faisal School and the Diplomatic Quarter schools serve the premium segment. For more affordable education, Indian-curriculum schools including International Indian School Riyadh, CBSE schools in Al Naseem and other areas charge SAR 8,000-15,000 (~€1,920-3,600) per year. Pakistani, Philippine, and other community schools also operate throughout the city. Riyadh's <a href="/saudi-arabia/education/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">school landscape</a> has expanded with new campus openings tied to Vision 2030 investment in education. Schools associated with compounds often prioritize compound residents for admission. Families should apply 6-12 months before the desired start date, as popular schools maintain waiting lists. School transport is widely available at SAR 3,000-6,000 (~€720-1,440) per year. The academic year begins in August for most international schools.</p>

  <h2>Healthcare Facilities</h2>
  <p>Riyadh has comprehensive healthcare options. King Faisal Specialist Hospital and Research Centre is the premier medical facility, offering advanced treatments including organ transplants and oncology. Dr. Sulaiman Al Habib Medical Group operates several modern hospitals across Riyadh with strong reputations for quality care. Saudi German Hospital, Dallah Hospital, and Kingdom Hospital provide private care popular with expat families. For government healthcare, the Ministry of Health operates King Fahd Medical City and numerous district hospitals. GP consultations at private clinics cost SAR 100-250 (~€24-60), while specialist visits run SAR 200-500 (~€48-120). All employers must provide CCHI-approved <a href="/saudi-arabia/healthcare/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">health insurance</a>, which typically covers hospitalization, outpatient care, and prescription medications. Riyadh also has a strong dental care sector, with routine check-ups at SAR 150-300 (~€36-72). Pharmacies are widely available, with chains like Nahdi Pharmacy and Al Dawaa providing extended-hours service across the city.</p>

  <h2>Entertainment and Social Life</h2>
  <p>Riyadh has transformed since 2017 from a relatively quiet capital to a city with a vibrant entertainment scene. Riyadh Season, the annual mega-festival running from October to March, attracts millions with concerts featuring major international artists, sporting events, theme parks, and cultural exhibitions across multiple zones. Boulevard Riyadh City is a year-round entertainment district with restaurants, shops, and event spaces. The upcoming Qiddiya project, covering 334 square kilometers southwest of the city, will be the largest entertainment destination in the kingdom, featuring theme parks, a Formula 1 circuit, golf courses, and nature reserves. Restaurants and cafes have multiplied exponentially, with international chains and independent venues offering everything from Japanese ramen to Neapolitan pizza. Sports events including Formula E, boxing championships, WWE events, and international football matches regularly visit the city. The art and design scene is growing through Diriyah Art Futures and the Noor Riyadh light festival. Weekend activities include desert camping, ATV rides in the surrounding dunes, visits to the Edge of the World (Jebel Fihrayn), and day trips to the historic Diriyah UNESCO site, which is being developed into a major cultural and tourism destination.</p>

